[4]
Date: Wed, 09 Apr 1997 16:01:07 -0400 (EDT)
From: Timothy W. Beth <BETH@A1.CBER.FDA.GOV>
Subject: Xenotransplantation; Clarification

This is just a clarification regarding FDA's procedures and policies and
Xenotransplantation. There were some minor yet important errors in the
previous e-mail.
FDA has not "Approved" the "Practice" of Xenotransplantation. There is no
Federal Law (or State, I believe) banning the procedure. In any case, FDA
approves products not procedures. Each Xeno-graft application will be
reviewed on an individual basis.
FDA also has not at present issued any REGULATIONS (i.e. requirements)
specifically regarding Xenotransplantation.
On September 23, 1996, FDA along with other PHS agencies issued DRAFT
Guidelines on the Infectious Disease Issues in Xenotransplantation. These
guidelines were issued for comment. These are not legal requirements but are
guidelines intended to help ensure the safety of the American public.
I think there is a misconception that FDA or the PHS is endorsing or
performing Xenotransplantation procedures. This is not true. However, FDA
does have a legal responsibility to evaluate all possible therapuetic
product applications that are sent to the Agency. It is also FDA's
responsibility to protect the public health regarding possible infectious
disease transmission.
Therefore, FDA and the other public health agencies issued the DRAFT
guidelines for comment and for guidance to help ensure that SPONSORS who
choose to pursue Xenotransplantation will contact the FDA regarding their
proposed investigations into possibly therapeutic products (as is required
by Federal Law) and protect their employees and the American public from
possible infectious disease transmission.
---
Timothy W. Beth
Consumer Safety Officer
Division of Regulations and Policy
Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research
U.S. Food and Drug Administration
Beth@a1.cber.fda.gov
